body:
As of https://github.com/bevyengine/bevy/pull/13693, `bevy_diagnostic` polls CPU info in a background task. This is good! 

Currently it queues a new background task on a more or less fixed interval, and gates the total number of tasks to be half the number of workers in the pool. This approach has several flaws:
+ It relies on information about the workers in the thread pool, which may not be available or consistent on all platforms.
+ It adds redundant load to the pool.
+ It can theoretically result in diagnostics being polled too frequently, resulting in garbage output.
+ It can theoretically deliver polling results out of order.

To avoid these issues, `bevy_diagnostic` should spawn a *single task* which:
1. Waits for the min-update period to pass.
2. Polls cpu the diagnostics.
3. Reschedules itself.

This can be easily implemented as a custom `Future` that always returns `Poll::Pending`, and which transmits results intermittently using an async-channel. The future can re-schedule itself eagerly, and read the CPU data only when enough time has passed since the previous update.

Here is a rough sketch:

```rust
struct DiagnosticJob {
    last_refresh: Option<Instant>,
    data_rx: Sender<SysinfoRefreshData>
}

impl Future for DiagnosticJob {
    type Output = ();

    fn poll(self: Pin<&mut Self>, cx: &mut Context<'_>) -> Poll<()> {
        // Reschedule this task
        cx.waker().wake_by_ref()
        // Determine if it's time to run diagnostics
        let run_diagnotsic = self
            .last_refresh.map(|t| t.elapsed() > MINIMUM_CPU_UPDATE_INTERVAL)
            .unwrap_or(true);
        // Run the diagnostics
        if run_diagnostic {
            let data = get_diagnostic_data();
            self.data_rc.send(data);
            self.last_refresh = Some(Instant::now());
        }
        // Yeild to the executor
        Poll::Pending
    }
```
